Date: Wed, 23 Feb 2000 01:12:35 -0800 (PST)
From: Maria Teresa Destro <destromt@yahoo.com>

Answering John Marr's question:
The newborns get infected because their mothers eat food contanining _L.
monocytogenes_ and the bacteria is able to cross the placenta barrier and
get to the
baby. Virulent strains of the microorganism are capable of multiplying in
macrophages, disrupting these cells and producing septecemia. In this
stage, the organism have access to other body areas, which may envolve the
central nervous system, the heart, or other locations and may invade the
fetus of pregnant women. The stage of pregnancy when invasion occurs
determines the outcome of the disease: abortion, stillbirth or neonatal
sepsis.
--
Maria Teresa Destro, Ph.D.
e-mail: destromt@yahoo.com
