[3
Date: Wed, 23 Feb 2000 08:10:46 -0500
From: Lurie, Perrianne <PLURIE@health.state.pa.us>

Neonatal listeriosis is acquired prenatally from maternal infection. So
newborns could easily have become infected by their mothers' ingestion of
the contaminated pork tongue in gelatin while still pregnant.
According to Chin's CONTROL OF COMMUNICABLE DISEASES MANUAL [(c) APHA,
2000, "The normal host who acquires infection may exhibit only an acute,
mild, febrile illness, but in pregnant women infection can be transmitted
to the fetus. Infants may be stillborn, born with septicemia, or develop
meningitis in the neonatal period even though the mother may be
asymptomatic at delivery. The postpartum course of the mother is usually
uneventful, but the case-fatality rate is 30% in newborn infants and
approaches 50% when onset occurs in the first four days..."
--
Perrianne Lurie, M.D., M.P.H., F.A.C.P.M.
Bureau of Epidemiology
Division of Communicable Disease Epidemiology
Pennsylvania Department of Health
