[4
Date: Wed, 23 Feb 2000 09:04:01 -0500
From: Marian Rodgers <mrodgers@cmc-dayton.org>

On the subject of newborn infection and its relationship to food borne
Listeria:
Reference: The American Academy of Pediatric's 1997 Pediatric Redbook, p. 328.
"Asymptomatic fecal and vaginal carriage [of _Listeria monocytogenes_ in
pregnant women can result in sporadic neonatal disease from transplacental
or ascending routes of infection or from exposure during delivery. Maternal
infection has been associated with abortion, preterm delivery, and other
obstetric complications. Late-onset neonatal infection can result from
acquisition of the organism during passage through the birth canal or from
environmental sources and the hematogenous invasion of the organism from
intestine."
Most of the documented cases in Listeria outbreaks are the
immunocompromised and weaker individuals. In such a food borne outbreak,
the majority of cases will not be diagnosed. Infection in an otherwise
healthy pregnant woman will often go unrecognized unless and until the
unborn child suffers and microbiological studies are done after delivery.
--
Marian Rodgers, RN, MPH
Infectious Disease Clinician
The Children's Medical Center
Dayton, Ohio
e-mail: mrodgers@cmc-dayton.org
